            <fr:addr>jms-018E</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-018E.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="decidability of regular expression matching">decidability of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017C.xml" title="regular expression matching" addr="jms-017C" type="local">regular expression matching</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0179.xml" title="regular expressions (abstract syntax)" addr="jms-0179" type="local">regular expression</fr:link> over an <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016H.xml" title="alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists an algorithm to compute whether a given <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016I.xml" title="string over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in \Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017D.xml" title="the matching relation for regular expressions" addr="jms-017D" type="local">matches</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:addr>jms-018E/0</fr:addr><fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-018E/0.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="decidability of regular expression matching › forest://jonmsterling/jms-018E/0"><fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-018E.xml" title="decidability of regular expression matching" addr="jms-018E" type="local">decidability of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017C.xml" title="regular expression matching" addr="jms-017C" type="local">regular expression matching</fr:link></fr:link> › jms-018E/0</fr:title><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <html:p>The idea of the proof is to find a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017L.xml" title="deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFA</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> satisfying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}=\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; so for this we need only <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-018A.xml" title="all regular languages are automatical" addr="jms-018A" type="local">Corollary <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-018A" /></fr:link> rather than the full <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-018B.xml" title="Kleene’s theorem" addr="jms-018B" type="local">Kleene’s theorem</fr:link>. Then our algorithm is to feed the given string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and check whether the final state is accepting or not.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<html:p>There is a subtlety in the argument above: we need the <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017L.xml" title="deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFA</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> to have computably decidable equality of states. The way to deal with this is that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> has a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00LX.xml" title="finite set" addr="jms-00LX" type="local"><html:em>finite</html:em></fr:link> set of states, and so <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L0.xml" title="isomorphic sets" addr="jms-00L0" type="local">isomorphic</fr:link> to a standard finite set of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}_{<n}]]></fr:tex>, which has computably decidable equality. A more important subtlety is that we need it to be computably decidable whether a given state is an accepting state, and we also need the transition function to be computable; any subset of a finite set is going to be decidable for roughly the same reason—ahead of time, we can enumerate it as a list of numbers in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}_{<n}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p></fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
